  <h1>How Section 1983 Works</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Riley Chen (RC), Employment &amp; Civil Rights Practice Lead. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>The four elements</h2>
  <p>To prevail on a &sect; 1983 claim, a plaintiff must prove: (1) the defendant acted under color of state law; (2) the defendant&rsquo;s conduct deprived the plaintiff of a right secured by the Constitution or federal law; (3) the deprivation caused actual harm; and (4) the defendant is not protected by qualified immunity or sovereign immunity.</p>
  <h2>Color of state law</h2>
  <p>The defendant must have acted in an official governmental capacity &mdash; not as a private citizen. An off-duty police officer making an arrest is acting under color of law. A government contractor may or may not qualify depending on how closely their function is intertwined with government. Private prisons run under government contracts typically satisfy the color of law requirement.</p>
  <h2>Constitutional violation</h2>
  <p>The plaintiff must identify the specific constitutional right violated. The most common are Fourth Amendment (unreasonable search and seizure, excessive force, unlawful arrest), Fourteenth Amendment (due process, equal protection), and First Amendment (retaliation for protected speech or association). Federal statutory rights (like certain civil rights statutes) are also actionable under &sect; 1983.</p>
  <h2>Qualified immunity</h2>
  <p>The primary defense for individual government officials. The two-prong test: (1) did the official violate a constitutional right? (2) was the right clearly established at the time of the conduct? Courts may address either prong first (<em>Pearson v. Callahan</em>, 2009). &ldquo;Clearly established&rdquo; requires a sufficiently analogous prior case &mdash; a standard critics argue is impossibly circular.</p>
  <h2>Monell liability for municipalities</h2>
  <p>Local governments cannot be held liable under respondeat superior. Instead, &sect; 1983 liability attaches only when the violation resulted from: (a) an official policy enacted by a final policymaker, (b) a widespread custom or practice, (c) a failure to train amounting to deliberate indifference, or (d) a single decision by a final policymaker. Monell claims require substantially more evidence than individual officer claims.</p>
  <h2>Damages</h2>
  <p>Compensatory damages: actual harm suffered. Punitive damages: available against individual officers with malice or reckless disregard; not available against municipalities. Nominal damages: when a constitutional right was violated but no actual harm is shown &mdash; traditionally $1 but may be more. Attorney fees: recoverable by the prevailing plaintiff under 42 U.S.C. &sect; 1988.</p>
